solutions.content:
We can view the official solution as a form of optimized dynamic programming solution.

With a naive dynamic programming solution, we can keep track of the lowest price encountered thus far using the folllowing relation:

* memo[i+1] is the lowest price up to prices[0..i]

The code becomes:

```java
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        int n = prices.length;
        if (n <= 1) {
            return 0;
        }

        int ans = 0;
        int[] memo = new int[n+1];
        memo[1] = prices[0];

        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            memo[i+1] = Math.min(memo[i], prices[i]);
            ans = Math.max(ans, prices[i] - memo[i]);
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```

It requires `~O(N)` space.

Noticing that we only ever need to keep track of the maximum solution of a subproblem, we can avoid allocating an array.

```java
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        int n = prices.length;
        if (n <= 1) {
            return 0;
        }

        int ans = 0;
        int lo = prices[0];

        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            ans = Math.max(ans, prices[i] - lo);
            lo = Math.min(lo, prices[i]);
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
```

Now it requires `~O(1)` space.

