solutions.content:
If we are in S1, it means we bought a stock at current time or we bought it in past.
If we are in S2, it means we sold a stock at current time or we sold it in past.

At beginning, only way to be in S1 is to buy stock at that time.
At beginning, there is no way to be in S2, so it is undefined (`INT_MIN`).

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2292f521-67ae-4f0d-bb59-db6389690725_1603536167.8704946.png)

**C++**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
        if(prices.size() < 2) {
            return 0;
        }
        int n = prices.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(2, vector<int> (n));
        dp[0][0] = -prices[0], dp[1][0] = INT_MIN;
        for(int i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
            dp[0][i] = max(dp[0][i - 1], -prices[i]);
            dp[1][i] = max(dp[1][i - 1], dp[0][i - 1] + prices[i]);
        }
        return max(0, dp[1][n - 1]);
    }
};
```

O(1) space can be achieved by utilizing the fact that only the previous state is required to construct current state.

Inspired by this [post](https://leetcode.com/problems/best-time-to-buy-and-sell-stock-with-cooldown/discuss/75928/Share-my-DP-solution-(By-State-Machine-Thinking))

