solutions.content:
This one is little tricky. Few things to notice here:
1. Function starts at the start of a time interval and ends at the end of the interval
    E.g. function(id=1) starts at the start of time = 2 second. If it was supposed to run for only one second, they would have written it like "2:end:2". It ends at the end of second 2. 
    That means, the  next function can be started at next timestamp. Or if there is a background function running, it can resume only in the next timestamp (which is 3)

2. A function DOES NOT end while some other function is running. E.g. this will never happen
    "0:start:0", "1:start:2", "0:end:3"

    That means for every "end", the running function is of the same id as that of the end

We use stack.
there are only two cases:
1. start or 2. end


**start:**
    We push this on the stack.
    Before pushing, we need to put the already running function on the background and add its run time to ans

**end:**
    Pop the top of the stack. This function has finished its complete run. Now, it's runtime will be
    `ret[stack.top.id] += current timestamp - prevTime + 1`
    We are adding 1 here because "end" gets executed for the whole of current timestamp.

**prevTime:**
    At each step, we update the prevTime with current time stamp. prevTime represents when actually current function started running (It can be because this function is "start"ed or resumed from background)


```
class Function {
    boolean isStart = false;
    int id, time;

    public Function(String[] val)
    {
        id = Integer.parseInt(val[0]);
        isStart = val[1].equals("start");
        time = Integer.parseInt(val[2]);
    }
}

class Solution {
    public int[] exclusiveTime(int n, List<String> logs) {

        int[] ret = new int[n];
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
            ret[i] = 0;

        Stack<Function> stack = new Stack<>();

        int prevTime = 0;

        for(String log: logs)
        {
            Function currFunc = new Function(log.split(":"));

            if(currFunc.isStart)
            {
                if(!stack.isEmpty())
                {
                    ret[stack.peek().id] += currFunc.time - prevTime;
                }

                stack.push(currFunc);
                prevTime = currFunc.time;
            }
            else
            {
                Function popped = stack.pop();
                ret[currFunc.id] += currFunc.time - prevTime + 1;

                prevTime = currFunc.time + 1; 
                // We write +1 here because the next function is going to start at next timestamp
                // or resumes at next timestamp
            }
        }

        return ret;
    }
}
```

