solutions.content:
According to the problem description, we can have at most 1 function running at the same time.
That means in terms of exclusive time calculation, any "start" log would immediately stop any running function.

The rules can be summerized as follows:
1. when the log is an `end` , it ends the function on top of the stack. The elapsed time is (log timestamp - previous timestamp + 1) (+1 because it is the `end` of the time)
2. whe th elog is a `start`, it pauses the function on top of the stack, which in terms of time calculation also means to END the the function on top of the stakc. The elapsed time is (log timestamp - previous timestamp) (no need to +1 because it is the `beginning` of the time)

That's all. 

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> exclusiveTime(int n, vector<string>& logs) {
        vector<int> ret(n);
        stack<int> ids;
        int prev_time = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<logs.size(); i++) {
            string log = logs[i];
            size_t first = log.find_first_of(":");
            size_t second = log.find_last_of(":");
            int id = stoi(log.substr(0, first));
            string event = log.substr(first+1, second-first-1);
            int timestamp = stoi(log.substr(second+1));
            if( event == "end" ) {
                ret[ids.top()] += (timestamp - prev_time+1);
                ids.pop();
                prev_time = timestamp + 1;
            } else if ( event == "start" ) {
                if(!ids.empty()) {
                    ret[ids.top()] += (timestamp - prev_time);
                }
                ids.push(id);
                prev_time = timestamp;

            }
        }
        return ret;
    }
};
```

