solutions.content:
The little trick here to make the code more consistent is to increment by one all "end events" as we parse them, since the end bound is inclusive. This way, we use `time - previousTime` to determine how long the caller function spent on its own. Then it's just a matter of identifying which function was the caller and we find this information by using a stack.

```
data class Log(val id: Int, val type: String, val time: Int) {
	companion object {
		fun from(s: String): Log {
			val parts = s.split(":")
			return Log(parts[0].toInt(), parts[1], if (parts[1] == "start") parts[2].toInt() else parts[2].toInt() + 1)
		}
	}
}

fun exclusiveTime(n: Int, rawLogs: List<String>): IntArray {
	val times = IntArray(n)

	val stack = Stack<Int>()
	var previousTime = 0
	for (rawLog in rawLogs) {
		val (id, type, time) = Log.from(rawLog)
		if (stack.isNotEmpty()) times[stack.peek()] += time - previousTime
		if (type == "start") stack.push(id) else stack.pop()
		previousTime = time
	}

	return times
}
```

