solutions.content:
Hopefully self documenting code, but added comments just in case. This uses two simple stack which runs about 90% faster than other solutions but more importantly, hopefully easier to read.

Obviously for more readabilty, a sub class would be created, but this is a compromise and this pattern can be applied to other problems that require complex items (multi dimension) on the stack. Introduced in William Fiset videos on BFS search.

```
class Solution {
    public static final String START = "start";
    public static final int PID = 0;
    public static final int CMD = 1;
    public static final int TIME = 2;
    public int[] exclusiveTime(int n, List<String> logs) {
        int[] count = new int[n];
        Deque<Integer> pidStack = new ArrayDeque<>();
        Deque<Integer> timeStack = new ArrayDeque<>();
        for(String entry: logs) {
            String[] curr = entry.trim().split(":");
            int pid_v = Integer.valueOf(curr[PID]);
            int time_v = Integer.valueOf(curr[TIME]);
            // nothing to do if it's a start, we just need
            // to add it to the stack for later accounting
            if (START.equals(curr[CMD])) {
                pidStack.offerFirst(pid_v);
                timeStack.offerFirst(time_v);
            } else {
            // this is an end entry, we're not going to add it but
            // take its counterpart (start) off since it's guaranteed
            // to finish first in single processing
                int pid = pidStack.pollFirst();
                int starTime = timeStack.pollFirst();

            // we figure out how long it's been running for 
			// by taking the current entries time (an end time)
            // and subtract it from the starting time(top of the stack)
			// but we need to add 1 to include
            // the starting unit, ex [5,8] => 5,6,7,8 => 4
                int dt = time_v - starTime + 1; // plus 1 to be inclusive of start

            // apply this time unit to its respective pid, which can be extracted
            // from the end entry or the top popped off pid value since they
            // would be the same
                count[pid] += dt;

            // now if there was another process on the stack, it needs to know
            // that this time slice was not part of its "total" accounting so
            // we will put a negative placeholder in its slot so when its end
            // arrives, we will have its interrupts accounted for 
			// total = (endTime - startTime - [interrupted times] + 1)
                if (!pidStack.isEmpty()) {
                    int topPid = pidStack.peekFirst();
                    count[topPid] -= dt;
                }
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

