solutions.content:
The problem already hints that you can use a stack for solving it, where you can keep track of the current function ID and whenever there's a `start`, we push the current function ID in the stack, and whenever there's an `end`, we pop the top of stack. The tricky part is getting the exclusive time while you're doing the stack operations so you can keep the `O(N)` time complexity. You can get this done by counting how long the current function has been as current. This changes whenever there is a `start` or `end`.

If you look at the example provided:
<img src="https://assets.leetcode.com/uploads/2019/04/05/diag1b.png" width="50%" />

You'll notice that whenever there is a `start`, the count starts at the beginning of the timestamp, but when there is an `end` the count stops at the end of the timestamp. This is an important implementation detail. So the solution goes like this:

* Track the current function ID as `currentId`. Initially with value -1, which means there is no call happening.
* Track the last timestamp read as `lastTimestamp`. Initially with value 0.
* Have an int array for holding the exclusive times for each function.
* For each log string:
	* If is a start:
		* If we have a current call (`currentId != -1`):
			* Add to its exclusive time the amount of time since the last timestamp (`startEventTimestamp - lastTimestamp`).
			* Push the current id into the stack.
		* Make the log id the current id.
		* Make the last timestamp the log's timestamp.
	* If is an end:
		* Add to the its exclusive time the amount of time since the last timestamp **plus 1**, as it needs to include that timestamp.
		* Make the last timestamp the log's timestamp **plus 1**.
		* Pop from the stack if not empty and make the output the current id.

Here the same in code (*Note: I used a private class to hold the log data to clean up a little bit*):
```
class Solution {
    public int[] exclusiveTime(int n, List<String> logs) {
        int[] result = new int[n];
        Stack<Integer> callStack = new Stack<>();
        int lastTimestamp = 0;
        int currentId = -1;
        for (String log : logs) {
            LogDetails details = new LogDetails(log);
            if (details.isStart()) {
                if (currentId != -1) {
                    result[currentId] += details.timestamp - lastTimestamp;
                    callStack.push(currentId);
                }
                currentId = details.id;
                lastTimestamp = details.timestamp;
            } else {
                result[currentId] += details.timestamp + 1 - lastTimestamp;
                lastTimestamp = details.timestamp + 1;
                currentId = callStack.isEmpty() ? -1 : callStack.pop();
            }
        }
        return result;
    }

    private class LogDetails {
        int id;
        String action;
        int timestamp;

        private LogDetails(String log) {            
            String[] split = log.split(":");
            this.id = Integer.parseInt(split[0]);
            this.action = split[1];
            this.timestamp = Integer.parseInt(split[2]);
        }

        private boolean isStart() {
            return "start".equals(this.action);
        }
    }
}
```

### Complexity
* Time complexity: `O(n)` as we iterate over the list of logs only once. Push and pop operations in stack are both `O(1)`, so they don't add to the complexity.
* Space complexity: `O(n)` as we are using a stack to store the function ids.

