solutions.content:
NOTE: The function that starts at the end (during the start spree), ends first (think of it as a stack)
 SO read a log and if it has 'start' in it, then simply put into stack
 When a log with 'end' comes, we know that the function that is ending has the 'start' log line on TOP os stack, so get it and compute time
 One thing to notice is once a function goes into stack, that function will have a 'wait time' until it resides in the stack and that is not computed in the time to run of that function

```
class Solution {
    public int[] exclusiveTime(int n, List<String> logs) {
        int[] res = new int[n];
        Stack<Log> stack = new Stack<>(); // to hold the func start

        for(String logLine : logs) {
            Log log = new Log(logLine); // create a log

            if(log.isStart) {
                stack.push(log);
            } else {
                Log logOnTop = stack.pop(); // get the top log (present log's start)
                res[log.id] +=  log.time - logOnTop.time + 1 - logOnTop.timeToWait;
                if(!stack.isEmpty()) {
                    stack.peek().timeToWait += log.time - logOnTop.time + 1; // update top log in stack's time to wait
                }
            }
        }

        return res;
    }
}

class Log {
    int id;
    int time;
    boolean isStart;
    int timeToWait;

    public Log(String logL) {
        String[] logLine = logL.split(":");

        this.id = Integer.parseInt(logLine[0]);
        this.time = Integer.parseInt(logLine[2]);
        this.isStart = logLine[1].equals("start");
        this.timeToWait = 0;
    }
 }
