solutions.content:
Use +1 for start, -1 for end operation. Create a stack of states, where state = {id, op, timestamp}
Only put start events on the stack. When you get an end event, pop the start event from the stack, because it means the function for the function execution on top of stack has ended
```
public int[] exclusiveTime(int n, List<String> logs) {
        Stack<int[]> stack = new Stack();
        int[] res = new int[n];
        for (int i = 0; i < logs.size();i++) {
            String[] vals =logs.get(i).split(":");
            int id = Integer.valueOf(vals[0]);
            int time = Integer.valueOf(vals[2]);
            int op = vals[1].equals("start") ? 1 : -1;

            if (op == 1) {
                if (!stack.isEmpty()) {
				// Whenever you get a start event, update the time for the previously executing event
                    res[stack.peek()[0]] += time - stack.peek()[1];
                }
                stack.add(new int[]{id, time});
            } else {
			// Whenever you get an end event, the event on the stack(currently executing function) will have the same id as that of the end event. Update the time 
			// of the currently executing function and pop it off the stack since it has completed
                int[] currTask = stack.pop();
                res[currTask[0]] += time-currTask[1]+1;
				// The next function inn the stack would start executuing as soon as the top event is popped. Update the execution start timestamp of the next function.
                if (!stack.isEmpty()) {
                    stack.peek()[1] = time+1;
                }
            }

        }

        return res;
    }
