solutions.content:
**Key point:**
* Like a real computer, we need a stack to push in functions.
* In the stack I save off the function start time and how long it was pushed in stack by other functions on top.
* When I encountered an end log entry, I trust the log was never messed up and it must match with the top entry in stack. In real life, I will always double check.
* The run time of any function is its end time + 1 - start time - wait in stack time.
* When a function is popped from stack, make sure the next function in stack accumulate its wait time.
```
  vector<int> exclusiveTime(int n, vector<string>& logs) {
    vector<int> ret(n, 0);
    vector<std::pair<int, int>> s;
    for (const string & log : logs) {
      size_t pos;
      int id = std::stoi(log, &pos);
      bool start = log[pos+1] == 's';
      int t = std::stoi(log.substr(pos+(start?7:5)));
      if (start)
        s.push_back({t, 0});
      else {
        std::pair<int, int> head = s.back();
        s.pop_back();
        ret[id] += t + 1 - head.first - head.second;
        if (s.size())
          s.back().second += t + 1- head.first;
      }
    }
    return ret;
  }
