solutions.content:
Just keep adding time to the exclusive time of the current function *i*
And substracting time from the exclusive time of the enclosing function.
The reason why this is faster than the Apprache 2 is it takes less add/sub under some scenarios.

Given a series of logs: s1 -- e1 -- s2 -- e2 -- s3 -- e3 -- s4 -- e4
My solution only take 4 x 2 = 8 times of add/sub
- 4 is the number of functions
- for each function duration calculation, 1 more operation is required  to update the res[]

On the other hand, Approache 2 would take 7 x 2 = 14 times of add/sub
- 7 is the number of gaps between the start/end points
- for each gap difference calculation, 1 more operation is required  to update the res[]

```
class Solution {
    public int[] exclusiveTime(int n, List<String> logs) {
        ArrayDeque<String[]> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
        int[] res = new int[n];

        for(String log : logs) {
            String[] logEntry = log.split(":");
            String type = logEntry[1];

            if("start".equals(type)) {

                stack.push(logEntry);

            } else if("end".equals(type)) {
                String[] funcStart = stack.pop();

                int id = Integer.parseInt(logEntry[0]);
                int start = Integer.parseInt(funcStart[2]);
                int end = Integer.parseInt(logEntry[2]);
                int duration = end - start + 1;

                /// Add duration to the time for the current func i
                res[id] += duration;

                /// If there is a enclosing function
                /// Subtract duration from the time for it
                if(!stack.isEmpty()) {
                    String[] parentFunc = stack.peek();
                    int pId = Integer.parseInt(parentFunc[0]);
                    res[pId] -= duration;
                }
            }
        }

        return res;
    }
}
